none: Northwestern vs. Iowa and Northwestern vs. Minnesota
Northwestern University (Evanston, Ill.). School of Music (Contributor)
Northwestern University (Evanston, Ill.). School of Music

Two performances by the Northwestern University Marching Band during the 1984 season. First, the Northwestern University Marching Band performs at the Northwestern Wildcats' game against the Iowa Hawkeyes in Dyche Stadium in Evanston, Illinois. Before taking the field for the pregame performance, the band performs the National Anthem, "Go U Northwestern," "Ghostbusters," and "Alma Mater" inside Dyche Stadium. Pregame performances continue on the football field as the University of Iowa Marching Band performs "Iowa Fight Song" and "Go U Northwestern." The Northwestern University Marching Band then performs the National Anthem, "Wildcat Fantasy," and "Go U Northwestern." Halftime performances by the University of Iowa Marching Band include "Pinball Wizard," Joe Jackson's "Target," and selections from "Jesus Christ Superstar." The theme for Northwestern's halftime performance was heroes and included the theme songs for "Perry Mason," "Shaft," and "Rocky." Sharlene Wells, Miss America 1985, joins the band for "Alma Mater." Postgame performances from both bands include "Iowa Fight Song," "Go U Northwestern," "Rock Around the Clock/Stout-Hearted Men," and "1984 Olympic Fanfare." John P. Paynter then conducts "Alma Mater." The The second performance is from the Northwestern Wildcats' game against the Minnesota Gophers in Minneapolis, Minnesota. Pregame performances by the Northwestern Marching Band include "Minnesota Rouser," "Wildcat Fantasy," and "Go U Northwestern." The Minnesota Marching Band performs the National Anthem, "Battle Hymn of the Republic," and "Minnesota Rouser."

Digitization of this collection was funded by a generous gift from the family of Music professor and bandleader John Phillip Paynter, who began his musical studies at Northwestern, graduating with a Bachelor of Music degree in 1950 and a Master's in Theory and Composition in 1951. Upon graduation, Paynter joined NU's faculty as the Director of the Marching Band. During his career at Northwestern, Paynter taught classes in band music, conducting, and arranging.
